Let \((\mathcal{X},\nu)\) denote the space–time domain equipped with a probability measure \(\nu\), where
\[\begin{gather*}
\mathcal{X}=A\times\mathcal{T}, \qquad \nu=\alpha\otimes\tau,
\end{gather*}\]
with \(\alpha\) the spatial probability measure and \(\tau\) the temporal probability measure. Let the true ocean heat content field be
\[\begin{gather*}
Y:\mathcal{X}\rightarrow\mathbb{R},
\end{gather*}\]
and define the population mean
\[\begin{gather*}
\mu = \int_{\mathcal X}Y(x)\,d\nu(x).
\end{gather*}\]
Suppose observations arise from a preferential sampling density \(w(x)\) satisfying
\[\begin{gather*}
\int_{\mathcal X}w(x)\,d\nu(x)=1.
\end{gather*}\]
The expected sampled mean is
\[\begin{gather*}
\int_{\mathcal X}Y(x)w(x)\,d\nu(x),
\end{gather*}\]
so that the preferential sampling bias is
\[\begin{gather*}
\boxed{\; B_{\mathrm{samp}} = \int_{\mathcal X} Y(x)\bigl(w(x)-1\bigr)\,d\nu(x). \;}
\end{gather*}\]
Because \(\int_{\mathcal X} w\,d\nu = 1\), this is exactly a covariance under \(\nu\) – the identity at the heart of the preferential-sampling literature (the design-based view of survey sampling (Horvitz and Thompson 1952); the continuous formulation of Diggle et al. (2010)):
\[\begin{gather*}
\boxed{\;B_{\mathrm{samp}} \;=\; \mathbb{E}[w\,Y] - \mathbb{E}[Y] \;=\; \mathbb{E}[(w-1)\,Y] \;=\; \operatorname{Cov}(w,\, Y)\;}
\end{gather*}\]
with \(\operatorname{Cov}(w,Y) = \int_{\mathcal{X}} (w-1)(Y-\mu)\,d\nu\), since \(\int_{\mathcal{X}}
(w-1)\,d\nu = \mathbb{E}[w] - 1 = 0\). Conditioning on the realized sampling configuration (so \(w\) is the deterministic weight of Bias decomposition, not the random atomic empirical measure), this holds as an exact identity for every realization – no distributional assumption on \(Y\) or on the sampling, and no grid. If floats sample independently of OHC, \(w \perp Y\) and the bias vanishes; bias arises precisely to the extent that the sampling intensity co-varies with the field (equivalently, \(\beta \ne 0\) in the log-linear intensity of Bias decomposition).

